=E2=80=9CA basic premise of Web3,=E2=80=9D   I once wrote, =E2=80=9Cis that=
 every product is simultaneously an investment opportunity=E2=80=9D:
If you sign up for a Web3 social network or chat room or trading venue or l=
et=E2=80=99s-buy-the-Constitution lark, you will get some of that project=
=E2=80=99s tokens, which will entitle you to use the project=E2=80=99s app =
or exchange or Constitution, and which will give you some notional say in t=
he decentralized governance of the project. Also the tokens will appreciate=
 in value if the project takes off and more people want to use it. It=E2=80=
=99s as if being an early user of Facebook or Uber also automatically made =
you a shareholder of Facebook or Uber, and when those services got huge you=
 got rich.
This has good points and bad points:
=09The good thing is that=C2=A0Web3 and crypto have solved the cold-start p=
roblem for network-effects businesses. It is hard to build a social network=
 or a marketplace or a ride-sharing app or lots of other businesses, becaus=
e those businesses are useful mainly if they have a lot of users, so they a=
re not very useful for their=C2=A0first=C2=A0users.=C2=A0But if you add a c=
rypto token, the first users get the most tokens, so they stand to get the =
richest, so there is a lot of incentive to join early =E2=80=94=C2=A0which =
means that lots of people join quickly and it=C2=A0becomes useful.=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9CThe basic idea,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Andreessen Horowitz partner  Chris Dixo=
n=C2=A0once tweeted,=C2=A0is that =E2=80=9Cearly on during the bootstrappin=
g phase when network effects haven=E2=80=99t kicked in, [you] provide users=
 with financial utility via token rewards to make up for the lack of native=
 utility.=E2=80=9D=09The bad thing is that every project is simultaneously =
a Ponzi scheme, and it is hard to know if people are using the project beca=
use they get utility out of it or because they hope to dump their tokens on=
 future suckers.

I will not belabor this =E2=80=94=C2=A0we=E2=80=99ve   talked about it   ex=
tensively a few times before =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I do feel like I have to me=
ntion Helium? Helium is, famously, The One Real Web3 Thing. =E2=80=9C Maybe=
 There's a Use Case for Crypto After All,=E2=80=9D was the headline of the =
New York Times article about it in February. Helium is a decentralized netw=
ork of wireless hotspots for internet-of-things devices like, for some reas=
on, online mousetraps (?). From that Times article:

Helium, which was founded in 2013, didn=E2=80=99t start off as a crypto com=
pany. Its founders originally tried to build a long-range, peer-to-peer wir=
eless network the old-fashioned way =E2=80=94 by persuading people and busi=
nesses to set up hot spots and stringing them together. But they struggled =
to get enough participants, and the network stalled.
Frank Mong, Helium=E2=80=99s chief operating officer, told me that the comp=
any was running out of money in 2017 when an engineer suggested, during an =
all-hands Scotch-drinking session, that more people might be willing to set=
 up hot spots if they could earn cryptocurrency by doing it.
=E2=80=9CThat incentive model, powered by crypto, actually made sense in th=
is case,=E2=80=9D Mr. Mong said.
So the company tore up its old business model and settled on a new one. Ins=
tead of building its network itself, Helium would make it fully decentraliz=
ed and let users build it themselves by buying and connecting their own hot=
 spots. Participants would be paid in crypto tokens, and they=E2=80=99d get=
 to vote on proposed ideas for changes to the network. If the price of thos=
e tokens rose, they=E2=80=99d make even more money, and set up even more ho=
t spots.
The new model, which was released in 2019, worked like a charm. Crypto fans=
 raced to set up Helium hot spots and start generating crypto tokens.=C2=A0

Great stuff. Helium  ran into controversy in July, which led to=C2=A0founde=
r Amir Haleem=C2=A0tweeting the incredible statistic that the network =E2=
=80=9Cgenerates around $2M/mo in fees,=E2=80=9D but that most of that is fr=
om =E2=80=9CHotspot onboarding fees,=E2=80=9D and only about $6,500 per mon=
th comes from data fees. Roughly 99.7% of Helium=E2=80=99s revenue comes fr=
om new users joining; roughly 0.3% comes from people actually using the pro=
duct, months=C2=A0after=C2=A0the Times article about how it=E2=80=99s actua=
lly useful. One day it might be actually=C2=A0used. But in the meantime, if=
 more people keep buying into it, it can be lucrative. Andreessen Horowitz =
led a  $111 million token sale for Helium in 2021.
Here, though, the point that I want to make is that this situation =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0every product is an investment =E2=80=94=C2=A0also has good points=
 and bad points as a matter of=C2=A0securities regulation:
=09The good thing is that if you are a venture-capital firm investing in We=
b3 or decentralized-finance projects, or a crypto exchange listing their to=
kens, you can say =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, this is a product, not a security.=E2=
=80=9D=09The bad thing is that if you are the US Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission and you want jurisdiction over all of DeFi and Web3, you can say =
=E2=80=9Call of these things are securities, not products.=E2=80=9D

And you=E2=80=99re both right! Everything is both. That is the economic inn=
ovation of crypto and DeFi and Web3, making everything both the currency of=
 a project and equity in that project.
Here=E2=80=99s  a speech that SEC Chair Gary Gensler gave today:

Of the nearly 10,000 tokens in the crypto market,=C2=A0I believe the vast m=
ajority are securities. Offers and sales of these thousands of crypto secur=
ity tokens are covered under the securities laws. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In general=
, the investing public is buying or selling crypto security tokens because =
they=E2=80=99re expecting profits derived from the efforts of others in a c=
ommon enterprise. ...
Some in the crypto industry have called for greater =E2=80=9Cguidance=E2=80=
=9D with respect to crypto tokens.
For the past five years, though, the Commission has spoken with a pretty cl=
ear voice here: through the DAO Report, the Munchee Order, and dozens of En=
forcement actions, all voted on by the Commission. Chairman Clayton often s=
poke to the applicability of the securities laws in the crypto space.
Not liking the message isn=E2=80=99t the same thing as not receiving it. =
=C2=A0
Investors are following crypto projects on social media and scouring online=
 posts about them. These tokens have promotional websites, featuring profil=
es of the entrepreneurs working on the projects.
It=E2=80=99s not about whether you set up a legal entity as a nonprofit and=
 funded it with tokens. It=E2=80=99s not whether you rely on open-source so=
ftware or can use a token within some smart contract. These are not laundro=
mat tokens: Promoters are marketing and the investing public is buying most=
 of these tokens, touting or anticipating profits based on the efforts of o=
thers.
Therefore, investors deserve disclosure to help them sort between the inves=
tments that they think will flourish and those that they think will flounde=
r. Investors deserve to be protected against fraud and manipulation. The la=
w requires these protections.

This just strikes me as uncontroversially, straightforwardly true as a matt=
er of standard US securities law, and I always wonder what people think the=
y are doing here. =E2=80=9CThe test,=E2=80=9D  the famous Supreme Court cas=
e says, =E2=80=9Cis whether the scheme involves an investment of money in a=
 common enterprise with profits to come solely from the efforts of others.=
=E2=80=9D If you=E2=80=99re buying tokens to bet on the success of some cry=
pto ecosystem or DeFi protocol or Web3 project =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if the pr=
oject=E2=80=99s promoters are=C2=A0selling those tokens to raise cash to de=
velop the ecosystem or protocol or project =E2=80=94=C2=A0what else could i=
t be?
On the other hand I also wonder what Gensler thinks he is doing here. From =
that same speech:

Joseph Kennedy, the first Chairman of the SEC, had a saying: =E2=80=9CNo ho=
nest business need fear the SEC.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
I=E2=80=99ve asked the SEC staff to work directly with entrepreneurs to get=
 their tokens registered and regulated, where appropriate, as securities. .=
..
Given the nature of crypto investments, I recognize that it may be appropri=
ate to be flexible in applying existing disclosure requirements. Tailored d=
isclosures exist elsewhere =E2=80=94 for example, asset-backed securities d=
isclosure=C2=A0differs from that for equities.

Really? I think that this understates the difficulty in =E2=80=9Capplying e=
xisting disclosure requirements=E2=80=9D to crypto, and overstates how help=
ful and nonthreatening the SEC is to honest crypto businesses. The SEC has =
been suing crypto projects for illegally issuing securities for   about fiv=
e years now, but in that time it has not issued any rules, or proposed any =
rules, or put anything on its  rulemaking agenda, about adapting the securi=
ties disclosure rules to crypto projects.
I do not think that that sort of adaptation is trivial. Think about what yo=
u would want to know about a crypto project before investing in it. Some of=
 what you would want to know =E2=80=94=C2=A0things like the qualifications =
of the founding team, their financial incentives and conflicts of interest,=
 where the money is going, how the project is capitalized, how they see the=
 market, what their business plan is, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is very similar t=
o what you=E2=80=99d want to know before investing in the stock of a compan=
y. But a lot would be different. You might care a lot less about the fundin=
g and capital structure of the entity that employs the developers to build =
the project, and a lot more about the structure and tokenomics of the decen=
tralized project itself.=C2=A0You might care a lot about the decentralized =
self-executing code of that project, since DeFi projects are   constantly g=
etting hacked, and you might want some sort of high-level summary of that c=
ode and its vulnerabilities rather than just a GitHub repository. In a trul=
y decentralized project, the people issuing the tokens might just not have =
access to some of the things =E2=80=94=C2=A0biographies of key players, aud=
ited financials =E2=80=94=C2=A0that are required in normal stock offerings.
And it=E2=80=99s not like most tokens these days are just sold by project d=
evelopers for cash to retail investors to raise money to build the projects=
. This used to be true, in the =E2=80=9Cinitial coin offering=E2=80=9D boom=
 of 2017, but the SEC   shut that down pretty hard. Now tokens are more lik=
ely to be earned (by mining, by staking, by running a hotspot) by ordinary =
participants, and if developers want to raise money they sell tokens to ven=
ture capital firms with long lock-ups. (You can sell securities to =E2=80=
=9Caccredited investors,=E2=80=9D like VCs, without registering them with t=
he SEC.) Adapting the securities-law framework to crypto would mean looking=
 at how crypto tokens actually come into the hands of retail investors, and=
 thinking about what sorts of protections they need in those transactions.
Also, much of Gensler=E2=80=99s speech is not about crypto=C2=A0issuers=C2=
=A0but about crypto=C2=A0intermediaries; the point is that if you operate a=
 crypto exchange, and if virtually all crypto tokens are securities, then y=
ou are running a securities exchange or at least a broker-dealer, and you s=
hould be required to follow SEC rules for exchanges. Again, as a legal matt=
er, I am sympathetic to that. But what does it actually mean for, for insta=
nce, decentralized finance? If a crypto exchange is just a set of self-exec=
uting smart contracts, if liquidity is provided by people depositing pairs =
of cryptocurrencies into automated market maker pools, then who registers t=
he exchange and who needs a broker-dealer license and how do the rules work=
? Or in centralized crypto finance, most crypto exchanges offer direct acce=
ss to retail customers, rather than requiring them to connect through broke=
rs. This is different from how traditional stock exchanges work, and in som=
e ways=C2=A0 arguably better, but you do have to think about how the tradit=
ional rules for broker-dealers and exchanges would apply. I am not saying t=
hat these are unanswerable questions; I am just saying that they are questi=
ons that the SEC might want to think about answering.
Meanwhile it is conspicuously the case that Gensler=E2=80=99s SEC mainly go=
es after the more law-abiding crypto actors. We talked a while back about h=
ow the SEC decided to shut down crypto exchanges=E2=80=99 yield products, w=
here investors can park their Bitcoins with an exchange and earn interest o=
n them. The SEC concluded that those products are securities, and while tha=
t is unintuitive I think it is probably correct under current law. And so  =
 it told Coinbase Global Inc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0a US-based, publicly listed ex=
change =E2=80=94=C2=A0not to do its yield product, and   fined BlockFi Inc.=
 $100 million for doing its yield product, and=C2=A0looked into=C2=A0stoppi=
ng Celsius Network and Voyager Digital Ltd. from doing their yield products=
, though it didn=E2=80=99t actually get around to shutting down Celsius and=
 Voyager before they went bankrupt.
In DeFi, on the other hand, there were projects like Olympus and Wonderland=
, which their=C2=A0users=C2=A0referred to as =E2=80=9CPonzis,=E2=80=9D and =
which offered=C2=A0absurd yields. When we   talked about this in January, i=
t had just been revealed that one of Wonderland=E2=80=99s pseudonymous=C2=
=A0leaders was a serial scammer who had co-founded Quadriga CX, the Canadia=
n crypto exchange that collapsed in an exit scam. Wonderland was offering y=
ields of 83,687.5% at the time.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CWhat is the difference betwee=
n Gemini and Wonderland,=E2=80=9D I asked, and I proposed that the main ans=
wer is that =E2=80=9CGemini answers the phone when the SEC calls=E2=80=9D
  [1]
:
There is a certain=C2=A0drunk-under-the-lamppost=C2=A0element to current U.=
S. crypto regulation. If you incorporate a company in the U.S. and walk int=
o the SEC=E2=80=99s office and ask =E2=80=9Chey what are we allowed to do,=
=E2=80=9D the answer is =E2=80=9Calmost nothing.=E2=80=9D If you just launc=
h the wildest thing in the world pseudonymously, call it =E2=80=9Cdecentral=
ized,=E2=80=9D and advertise eye-popping investment returns to U.S. investo=
rs, then, I mean, I don=E2=80=99t want to give you legal advice, but look a=
round.
In crypto,=C2=A0only=C2=A0the honest businesses need fear the SEC. The ince=
ntives are bad.
It is such a strange approach. On the one hand, I completely sympathize wit=
h Gensler=E2=80=99s view that virtually all of crypto should be under the j=
urisdiction of the SEC:
=09He is an ambitious financial regulator, and so he wants to have power ov=
er this big and interesting area of finance.=09He is more or less completel=
y right on the law: This stuff is all securities, so the securities regulat=
or should regulate it.=09He is right to worry: Lots of crypto stuff is scam=
my, or at least risky and under-disclosed, so as a consumer protection matt=
er the SEC should demand more disclosure and fewer scams.

On the other hand, if you are an ambitious financial regulator who wants to=
 regulate crypto, you have to regulate crypto! You have to=C2=A0put in the =
work! You have to sit down to try to understand how the crypto market opera=
tes, what investors need to know, and what is required to encourage useful=
=C2=A0capital formation. You have to write rules=C2=A0that anyone can read =
and that=C2=A0create some plausible path for how crypto developers can regi=
ster their tokens and how exchanges can trade them. And then you have to fo=
cus your enforcement efforts on actual consumer protection, going after the=
 crooks instead of just the people who are naive enough to walk into your o=
ffice.
If you don=E2=80=99t do that, then, what? Then the US will not be a leader =
in crypto innovation, is the traditional answer, and US investors will not =
have access to all the great crypto projects. As a consumer protection matt=
er, I can see why Gensler might find this answer dumb. Crypto prices have c=
rashed, and I suspect Gensler thinks that a lot of these projects are scams=
 anyway, and so missing out on them might be broadly good for US investors.=
=C2=A0
Still I do not understand the game here. Gensler=E2=80=99s posture seems li=
ke a massive bet against crypto ever being important.=C2=A0His message is b=
asically =E2=80=9CI should be the main regulator of crypto, and as the main=
 regulator my plan is mostly to ban it.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s not, abstra=
ctly, an insane posture: That=E2=80=99s more or less the view that the US D=
rug Enforcement Agency takes toward cocaine, for instance. (Or the view tha=
t   China takes toward crypto, for that matter.) But most of the people who=
 are jockeying to be the main regulator of=C2=A0crypto want to regulate a t=
hriving ecosystem; they want it to be big, and they want to be in charge of=
 it. Gensler wants to be in charge of it and have it be irrelevant and cumb=
ersome and slow-moving.
That=C2=A0might=C2=A0be a good pitch, now, in the crypto winter, when so ma=
ny crypto stories are about people losing their life savings to unregulated=
 scams. But it is not going to appeal to anyone in the crypto industry, and=
 I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s going to appeal to the politicians who =
are interested in crypto and who are  writing their own legislation to deci=
de who should regulate it. Gensler=E2=80=99s posture is that he should be i=
n charge of writing the rules for crypto, but not write them. I don=E2=80=
=99t see how that can work.

