=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> a story about</a>, you know, play-to-earn video games, non-fu=
ngible tokens, etc.:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to Kossar, NFT renting mechanisms in=
 play-to-earn games are important to keep them accessible to poorer players=
. =E2=80=9CYou have people that have money, but don=E2=80=99t have the time=
 to play the game, and on the other hand, you have people that don=E2=80=99=
t have money but have time,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He sees a future, however, where guild ownersh=
ip and management could upend the model of wealthy Western players managing=
 those in low-income countries. =E2=80=9CFilipinos could band together to b=
uy some assets and then rent them out to themselves and make money that way=
,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But he also envisions NFT games that could exp=
loit the wealth gap between players to deliver a different experience. =E2=
=80=9CWith the cheap labor of a developing country, you could use people in=
 the Philippines as NPCs (=E2=80=9Cnon-playable characters=E2=80=9D), real-=
life NPCs in your game,=E2=80=9D said Kossar. They could =E2=80=9Cjust popu=
late the world, maybe do a random job or just walk back and forth, fishing,=
 telling stories, a shopkeeper, anything is really possible.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, I do not mean to be too=
 naive a cheerleader for the prospects of artificial intelligence, but I do=
 think that within my lifetime AI will reach a point where it can=C2=A0<em>=
play the NPCs in a video game?=C2=A0</em>Like, the job of =E2=80=9Cjust wal=
k back and forth=E2=80=9D in a video game is absolutely absolutely absolute=
ly going to be automated out of existence, in the sense that it has already=
 been automated out of existence, in the sense that it has never been a job=
, in the sense that video games have software that can make a non-player ch=
aracter walk back and forth automatically, in the sense that that software =
is what a video game=C2=A0<em>is</em>. Obviously automating that job is che=
aper than paying someone in the Philippines to do it. Imagine launching Pac=
-Man in 1980 and being like =E2=80=9Cof course we=E2=80=99ll have to=C2=A0h=
ire some remote workers in developing countries to play the ghosts.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0Crypto economics is just wild, man.</p>
